My 2122 predictions:

-If a lot of the world of 1922 has commonalities with 2022, then there will be even less of a difference between 2022 and 2122 overall.

-The biggest change will be in living standards. Most people in Africa will live like people in China today, most people in the 'second world' will live like the first world of today, and most people in the first world, the OECD countries, will live like millionaires do today. While poverty might still exist in the poorest countries in the world, extreme poverty and subsistence farming will for the first time in history be completely eliminated.

-Nothing spectacular will happen regarding clothing styles, e.g. I predict jeans and T-shirts will still be a thing in some form. The transition from suits to casual wear in the 20th century represents a transition from formality to comfort and I see no likelihood of it reverting back. Perhaps shoelaces will definitely become a thing of the past. 

-There will be a revolution in surfaces and materials science in general. This will greatly reduce the load for housework. Self-cleaning surfaces will be everywhere. You'll literally be able to eat off the floor. Clothes will also be self-cleaning. Screens will be easily foldable and easily encompass entire walls.

-The trend towards austerity will continue. Material goods will not be in high regard. Only a select few gadgets like the smartphone will be indispensible. I predict some sort of a virtual environment will blow up in popularity and property there will be highly sought for, with more money being able to buy richer and more immersive virtual experiences.

-Your virtual presence will in turn affect your presence in the real world. Imagine just going into a shop, taking whatever you want and simply leaving with the cameras automatically recognizing you, recognizing what you took and deducting it from your bank account.

-Long distance relationships and families will be possible. With the use of virtual walls you'll be able to watch a game together with your dad who is in a hotel room on a completely different continent. It will be like he is in the same room except for physical contact and even there there might be some breakthroughs primarily geared towards long distance couples. 

-Temprary work related stays in richer foreign countries will balloon. It is a good model. The native populace is placated that the work force will not stay for good, labor shortages are addressed and the workers coming have a real chance to make a lot of money for the standards of their home country. Moreover, the temporary nature of the stay and the prospect of a prolonged rest period after this surplus of money is made makes it psychologically much easier to work hard and devote yourself to work.

-Nanotechnology will make significant breakthroughs and could have many applications in medicine, perhaps even increasing the human lifespan after a prolongued period of stagnation in that regard.

-I believe the pace of space exploration will significantly quicken in the coming decades in comparison with this relatively sluggish half-century after the moon landings. My optimistic predictions are that we will have a presence on the Moon roughly equivalent to what we have today on Anctarctica, with even an occasional rich tourist visiting the Moon, and we will have a presence on and around Mars roughly equivalent to 50 or so people. We will have probed Europa and Enceladus and perhaps have found first life outside of Earth. We might by that time even launch first probes towards Proxima Centauri (to study its exoplanet up close) at perhaps a couple percentages of the speed of light, with the journey taking roughly 100 years.

-The number of people on this planet will peak at less than 10 billion and start to gradually decrease. Where migrants are insufficient, unwanted or unsuitable, robots will take place for easy-to-program menial task. The only part of the world with a consistently growing population will be sub-Saharan Africa, and they will as a result take a much more dominant position in the world, somewhat analogous to China of today, who will in 2122 be far more like what Japan is today. Undoubtedly, this will create lots of social upheaval. 

-There will be a global conflict of some sort, most likely a prolongued cold war, between the Globalists and Nationalists, the division being whether you're in favor or against the current political and cultural order espoused by rich and powerful Western countries. 

-Moore's Law will no longer apply. Advances in computer technology will plod along very slowly if at all as computers simply reach the known capacities of the universe. This is not to say there won't be developments and improvements, but for most uses, computers will already be beyond strong enough. 

-Socially, loneliness will be seen as a public problem to be addressed on a statewide level, similarly to how it is currently starting in Japan. Social mores will be more encouraging of public interaction, especially with the elderly. The state will also have to take a bit of a role in matchmaking in order to stave off large rates of childlessness, on a voluntary basis of course. 

-Global warming will stop being an all-encompasing hot-button issue that it is today, similarly to the resolution of the ozon hole. Advances in green tech will slow global warming to a crawl. There will still be consequences, but as usual, rich countries will adapt and poor countries will suffer. Canada and Russia will have a large interest to warm large stretches of land and expand their habitable zones, while the first hear shields in extremely hot areas might be tested for the first time.

-Culture is of course the most difficult to predict. I certainly predict that radical progressivism will reach a saturation point and people will grow sick of its extensive moralising. It's always the first habringers of social change that tend to be the most strident, they have to be, but sooner or later these kinds of radicalisms outgrow their usefulness. 

To sum up... if will be a lot like today, except a bit richer and more technologically advanced. I certainly hate those hoary cliches where in some distant future a whole 20 years ago the world is unrecognizable in comparison with today.

Pretty close. He even called the energy shortage. The problem seems chiefly that he didn't spend more time thinking about that little shortage, and thus ends with this fairly optimistic view. He makes the same mistake that many of his contemporaries made, and that technophiles today make: without energy, tech is simply art fixtures. Without our millions of daily oil barrels, tech can no longer serve us, and while the author's predictions have largely proved accurate to this point, the loss of energy will mean that *our* future will look more and more like *his* past. We did discover nuclear energy, but it's simply not enough to keep our world developing as we have been. Same with solar, wind, and other "renewables." They also aren't enough, and we didn't find a way to build them without non-renewable materials. I sincerely credit the author for his predictions, but I only wish that I could share in his hopeful optimism of the future.

I find it painfully ironic that this writer who seemingly had great insight go his first claim utterly and completely wrong.  The claim that discovery brings about its own extinction, that the more we discover, the less there is to discover.

â€œItâ€™s turtlesâ€¦ I mean discoveries all the way down!â€

Yes and no. There is always more to discover. But more and more of it is just ever-more precise minutia of things we already know. Atoms to electrons to quarks to....string theory maybe. We're not likely to discover the next electricity anytime soon.

Nonsense, he was is absolutely one hundred and ten percent correct in this and it's a point far, FAR too many futurists utterly ignore. Knowledge is a finite resource the more of it obtained, the less there is to discover, but more critically the most important and truly fundamental discoveries are often the first to be found and anything that follows after is more like scientific pedantry then discovery. IMO the only fields left where truly society altering, really huge breakthroughs are possible is in biology, though these will come much more slowly then many would like because they are extremely complex systems. 

The reality is that our increasing understanding of the world has also lead to an increasing understanding of what's even theoretically possible at all. Back in 1920 it might've still been conceivable that anti-gravity or sci-fi style force fields could be possible in a hundred years with some new discovery, but nowadays we understand enough about physics to know that both of those are functionally impossible at a macro scale that would actually matter technologically.
The rate of innovation in pretty much every field has been decreasing for decades.

A {S curve} is a Perfect way to describe how things play out. (There will always be more to discover like some say) BUT the key factor is, we usually have stages. Where things get introduced, then we have a upgrading & fine tuning period which refines ideas and discoveries. Then we deal with troubleshooting how it fits interwoven with-in Society, Nature, Human behavior, etc. Plus the S curve really seems most accurate because still up until this current day, we constantly struggle with "economic struggles" and quality of Life conditions for people. We advance but we still have low income, poor people. How does society deal with that? If we make adjustments, will those adjustments still help once we further progress? It all really really depends on people's perspective and outlook towards "economic struggles" and how we can go about it as society progresses.  Thus a {S curve} feels pretty spot on.

I think I could make a categorical statement here and say everything concerning economics here is wrong: While there was a trend of nationalising industries through a lot of the 20th century there have been frequent instances of privatisation. The prevalence of unions has deteriorated considerably. Women having employment is not always a choice, as implied here, but very often an economic obligation. The capacity to amass wealth has not passed in the United States, or even really in the United Kingdom (recent events notwithstanding), I think the notion of there being limited potential in a country in this manner is silly, and quite contradicted. 

The population part was interesting, although the notion that governments could conduct policy for things as long term as future labour forces is laughable. Also the equilibrium between overpopulation and a labour force discounts the option of immigration as a quick and easy supplement for the natural growth of the national population, which is strangely alluded to in this same article with the mentions of better transportation and a harmonised American culture.

Sorry if I appear too nit-picky, this on the whole is very accurate for what it is. Usually past predictions for our time say more about their time than it does ours. While this example certainly does reflect the 1920s, I must admit it's one of the better sets of predictions I've seen.

Wow! Incredibly right and yet incredibly off at the same time. I think the computer revolution was just impossible to foresee, and therefore the cultural changes stemming from everyone and everything being at our fingertips has been lost. It is clear that the average American today is far more individualistic and self-reliant than he could have imagined, and the women a far more equal force than he foresaw as well. He could not have guessed world war two, and with it the rise of suburbia, the age of American dominance, and the bastardization of socialism through the communist revolutions and the cold war. I think he misjudged the future power of corporations to a great degree--he clearly did not think that they would end up having a far larger voice in politics and in community thinking as they have had. And that really stems from corporate dominance in the realm of TV, movies, and now on the internet. While he thought wealth would spread out (a realistic assumption from that time), it has instead become completely unhinged, and has fallen into the hands of a select few robber barons in the modern day. War, as he predicted, did fade off in its scale, but not for the reasons he discussed. Rather, it was the outright rejection of agreements in WW2, that complete unchecked aggression, and the development of atomic weapons that truly did away with global warfare. To a lesser extent, so too did the advent of international law and organizations, although they are not nearly robust enough to be credited in a major way there. It was truly astonishing how on one hand, he was absolutely correct about air travel--it is indeed 8 hours from the US to Europe--and yet wrong about the potential of rail. He thought that commercial steamers would have a "coastal role" (they would not), while modern rail has actually remained a valuable method of transport in freight and individual. Sadly, he completely missed the modern division in the United States, which itself stems from the internet, immigration, and contentious two party politics. While the US was indeed coming together up and through 9/11, that progress has reversed course and is now uncertain. Such a great video! Paleo-futurism is fascinating to listen to.

Open G (DGDGBD) tuning, Capo on 2

Intro           G C G / C G / G C G / C G / D G / C G / D G
Verses       G C G / C G / G C G / C G / D G / C G / D G
Interlude    G C G / C G / G C G / C G / D G / C G / D G
Outro          G C G / C G / G C G / C G / D G / C G / D G

[Intro]

[Verse 1]
Well I worked all summer couldn't save a cent
I gave all my money to the government
I don't know quite how it got spent
But the banks are coming for my deed
Man at the mill can't see,
Won't you let me get my feed for free, boys
Ain't that the way it is

[Verse 2]

I traded my stock for a V-8 Ford
Dad's .410 down on the floor board
And the titles wrote down to me, boys
That gasoline ain't free, boys
This clutch wearin' out my knee
Ain't that the way it is

[Interlude]

[Verse 3]
Well I met me a woman down in St. Paul
I even met her mother and I met her Pa
But her brother told me he'd bust my jaw
If I talked to his sister again
Told me I couldn't win
There's blood running down my chin now
Ain't that the way it is

[Verse 4]
Well I slept all night on the bar room floor
And woke up this morning my head was sore
Pockets empty but I want some more
The bar man's got my car
Tabs worth more by far
I'll leave her down at the bar now
Ain't that the way it is

[Interlude]

[Verse 5]
Well I hitched me a ride on the way back home
I got a job on a family farm
Times are hard here but I can't roam
And I ain't got nothing more
I owe that company store
Road's looking good for sure
Ain't that the way it is

[Verse 6]
Well I worked all summer couldn't save a cent
I gave all my money to the government
I don't know quite how it got spent
But the banks are coming for my deed
Man at the mill can't see
To let me get my feed for free
Ain't that the way it is

[Outro]
